 the responsibilities of the powerful in using incentives? Ruth Grant shows that, like all other forms of power, incentives can be subject to abuse, and she identifies their legitimate and illegitimate uses. Grant offers a history of the growth of incentives in early twentieth-century America, identifies standards for judging incentives, and examines incentives in four areas--plea bargaining, recruiting medical research subjects, International Monetary Fund loan conditions, and motivating students. In every case, the analysis of incentives in terms of power yields strikingly different and more complex judgments than an analysis that views incentives as trades, in which the desired behavior is freely exchanged for the incentives offered. Challenging the role and function of incentives in a democracy, Strings Attached questions whether the penchant for constant incentivizing undermines active, autonomous citizenship. Readers of this book are sure to view the ethics of incentives in a new light.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIncentive (Psychology). 0aMotivation (Psychology). 0aPolitical ethicsvElectronic books. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aPolitical psychology. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Information Management.2bisacsh  aInternational Monetary Fund loans.  aInternational Monetary Fund.  aaccountability.  aautonomy.  abehavioral pedagogy.  achange.  achildren.  achoice.  acompensation.  ademocracy.  ademocratic politics.  adisincentives.  aethical incentives.  aethics.  aexchange.  aexploitation.  agovernment policy.  aincentives.  aloan policies.  amanipulation.  amedical research subjects.  amotivation.  aoffer.  apersuasion.  aplea bargaining.  apower.  apractical judgment.  apurpose.  ascientific management.  asocial control.  asocial engineering.  ast